Part 1.3 b - Share insights on correlation

Lets take each feature one by one

I considered

( > 0.70 and < -0.70 => strong correlation

0.70 to 0.30 and -0.70 to -0.30 => moderate correlation

< 0.30 and < -0.30 => weak correlation )

1.P_incidence

This is strongly correlated with S_slope(0.81) and L_angle(0.72).

This is moderately correlated with S_Degree(0.64) and P_tilt(0.63).

This is Weakly correlated with P_radius(-0.25).

2.P_tilt

This is strongly correlated no other feature

This is moderately correlated with P_incidence(0.63), L_angle(0.43) and S_Degree(0.40)

This is Weakly correlated with S_slope(0.06) and P_radius(0.03)

3.L_angle

This is strongly correlated with L_angle(0.72)

This is moderately correlated with S_slope(0.60),S_Degree(0.53) and P_tilt(0.43)

This is Weakly correlated with P_radius(-0.08)

4.S_slope

This is strongly correlated with P_incidence(0.81)

This is moderately correlated with L_angle(0.60), S_Degree(0.52) and P_radius(-0.34)

This is Weakly correlated with P_tilt(0.06)

5.P_radius

This is strongly correlated with no other feature

This is moderately correlated with S_slope(-0.34)

This is Weakly correlated with P_incidence(-0.25), P_tilt(0.03), L_angle(-0.08) and S_Degree(-0.03)

6.S_Degree

This is strongly correlated with no other feature

This is moderately correlated with P_incidence(0.64), L_angle(0.53), S_slope(0.52) and P_tilt(0.40)

This is Weakly correlated with P_radius(-0.03)

Insights

Lets do feature by feature

  1. P_incidence

Univariate analysis:

Here, Type_S class has near to normal distribution whereas Type_H & Normal class has right-skewed distribution

Bivariate analysis:

This has a postive correlation with P_tilt, L_angle, S_Degree and S_slope so when P_incidence increases also increasing This don't have much correlation with other features.

  1. P_tilt

Univariate analysis:

Here, Normal class has near to normal distribution whereas Type_H & Type_S class has right-skewed distribution

Bivariate analysis:

This has a postive correlation with P_incidence, S_Degree so when P_tilt increases also increasing This don't have much correlation with other features.

  1. L_angle

Univariate analysis:

Here, Normal,Type_H & Type_S class has right-skewed distribution

Bivariate analysis:

This has a postive correlation with P_incidence, S_Degree and S_slope so when L_angle increases also increasing This don't have much correlation with other features.

  1. S_slope

Univariate analysis:

Here, Normal,Type_H & Type_S class has right-skewed distribution

Bivariate analysis:

This has a postive correlation with P_incidence, S_Degree and L_angle so when S_slope increases also increasing This don't have much correlation with other features.

  1. P_radius

Univariate analysis:

Here, Normal,Type_H & Type_S class has near to normal distribution

Bivariate analysis:

This don't have much correlation with any other features.

  1. S_Degree

Univariate analysis:

Here, Normal & Type_H class has near to normal distribution , Type_S class is right-skewed distribution

Bivariate analysis:

This has a postive correlation with all other features except P_radius so when S_Degree increases also increasing

Part 1.5 a - Experiment with various parameters to improve performance of the base model

Let do hyperparamater tuning to find the best K value

In [ ]:
train_score = {}
test_score = {}
n_neighbors = np.arange(1, 50, 1)
for neighbor in n_neighbors:
    KNN = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=neighbor)
    KNN.fit(X_train, y_train)
    train_score[neighbor]=KNN.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_score[neighbor]=KNN.score(X_test, y_test)
In [ ]:
plt.plot(n_neighbors, train_score.values(), label="Train Accuracy")
plt.plot(n_neighbors, test_score.values(), label="Test Accuracy")
plt.xlabel("Number Of Neighbors")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.title("KNN: Hyperparamter tuning of K-paramter")
plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Hyperparamter is done by varing K values and found best suited K value , when k is 17 its perfoming well without overfitting and underfitting So, I am choosing K=17
